\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 13. T. dolopicus} Form.,{\i  Deutsche Bot. Monatsschr. }{\b 15}: 75 (1897). Plant with creeping woody primary branches bearing axillary leaf-clusters and erect to ascending flowering stems up to 10 cm. Leaves 6-10 × 1-1·5 mm, narrowly lanceolate-spathulate, shortly petiolate, velutinous, the basal half ciliate; margins subrevolute. Inflorescence capitate, ovoid to globose. Bracts 1·5-4 mm wide, similar to the leaves or oblong-ovate, greenish. Calyx 4·5-5·5 mm; upper teeth c. 1·5 mm, lanceolate, ciliate. Corolla pink-purple, the tube scarcely exceeding calyx. •{\i  Mountains of N. & C. Greece.} Gr.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28 {\b  T. leucotrichus} Halácsy,{\i  Consp. Fl. Graec.}{\b  2}: 561 (1902), a seldom-collected plant of the high mountains of C. & S. Greece, is like {\b 13} but with leaves linear-lanceolate, sessile, covered by long and short hairs, and purplish bracts. Its status is uncertain, as is also that of {\i T. teucotrichus} var. {\i creticus} (Bald.) Ronniger from Kriti. Similar, possibly conspecific, taxa occur in Anatolia.
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28    {\b 14. T. cherlerioides} Vis., {\i Ill. Pi. Grecia:} 8 (1842) ({\i T. boissieri} Halácsy,{\i  T. hirsutus} auct., non Bieb.; incl. {\i T. pseudohumillimus} Klokov & Schost.,{\i  T. tauricus} Klokov & Schost.). Caespitose, with long, creeping branches bearing axillary leaf-clusters and erect flowering stems 1-8 cm. Leaves 4-10(-15) × 0·3-1 mm, linear to linear-lanceolate, sessile, glabrous or puberulent to velutinous, usually herbaceous; veins indistinct; margins more or less revolute, ciliate at least in basal half. Bracts up to 2·5 mm wide, more or less similar to the leaves, sometimes purple. Calyx 3·5-5 mm, tubular-campanulate; upper teeth 1-2 mm, lanceolate, usually ciliate and purple. Corolla 5-7 mm, pink; tube cylindrical. 2n = 28. {\i Mountains of C. part of Balkan peninsula; Krym.} Al Bu Gr Ju Rs (K).
\par

\par

\pard\f0\fs28  Variable in leaf- and bract-shape, and indumentum. Some local variants may deserve subspecific rank but a more thorough knowledge is needed of the variation pattern of the species in S.W. Asia.
\par

